<ArticleLayout
  title="Laundry Organisation Ideas That Actually Save Space"
  description="Practical laundry organisation ideas for Australian homes, apartments and units, including storage, drying, cleaning supplies and small-space routines."
  category="Laundry"
  date="Updated July 2026"
  readingTime="8 minute read"
  image="/images/laundry.webp"
  imageAlt="A practical laundry room with warm finishes, tidy storage and natural light"
>
  <p>
    Australian laundries are often asked to do too much with too little space. In many homes,
    the laundry is not just for washing clothes. It also becomes the place for cleaning
    products, pet supplies, spare towels, school uniforms, ironing, buckets, mops and overflow
    household storage.
  </p>
  <p>
    That can make a small laundry frustrating very quickly, especially when wet washing is
    waiting for a rack, baskets sit in the walkway or cleaning products gather around the
    tub. A renovation is not usually the first answer. A calmer routine often starts with
    clearing what does not belong and choosing fewer, better-placed items.
  </p>
  <p>
    This guide covers laundry organisation ideas that actually save space in everyday
    Australian homes.
  </p>

  <h2>Start by deciding what belongs in the laundry</h2>
  <p>
    Decide what the laundry should actually hold before adding more baskets, shelves or
    organisers.
  </p>
  <p>Some items make sense in the laundry:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Laundry detergent and stain removers.</li>
    <li>Pegs and drying accessories.</li>
    <li>Cleaning cloths.</li>
    <li>Buckets and basic cleaning tools.</li>
    <li>Spare towels or tea towels.</li>
    <li>Pet towels or washable mats.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Other items may be taking up valuable space without needing to be there. Bulk toilet
    paper, rarely used appliances, old paint tins, spare bags, Christmas decorations and
    random household overflow can often be moved somewhere else.
  </p>
  <p>
    A small laundry works best when it is treated as a working space, not a storage room for
    everything that has no other home.
  </p>

  <h2>Use vertical wall space</h2>
  <p>
    Many laundries have unused wall space above the washing machine, sink or bench.
    Wall-mounted shelves, cabinets or rails can make a major difference without taking up
    floor space.
  </p>
  <p>Good items for vertical storage include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Detergent.</li>
    <li>Fabric softener.</li>
    <li>Stain remover.</li>
    <li>Laundry soakers.</li>
    <li>Cleaning sprays.</li>
    <li>Spare cloths.</li>
    <li>Peg baskets.</li>
    <li>Small storage tubs.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Closed cabinets can make the room look tidier, while open shelves make everyday items
    easier to reach. For a small laundry, the best choice depends on how visible the room is
    from the rest of the home.
  </p>
  <p>
    If the laundry is part of a hallway, kitchen or bathroom, closed storage may be worth
    considering. If it is behind a door, open shelving can be simpler and more practical.
  </p>

  <h2>Add a slim storage trolley</h2>
  <p>
    A slim rolling trolley can be useful in narrow gaps, especially beside a washing machine,
    dryer or laundry sink.
  </p>
  <p>It can hold:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Laundry liquid.</li>
    <li>Stain remover.</li>
    <li>Dryer sheets.</li>
    <li>Cleaning brushes.</li>
    <li>Pegs.</li>
    <li>Spare cloths.</li>
    <li>Small pet cleaning supplies.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Measure the gap carefully. Check width, depth and height, and make sure the trolley can
    still roll out easily when loaded.
  </p>
  <p>
    A trolley is most useful when it solves a real access problem. If it becomes another place
    to stack random products, it will quickly add to the clutter rather than fixing it.
  </p>

  <h2>Keep laundry products grouped</h2>
  <p>
    Laundry products are easier to manage when they are grouped by task.
  </p>
  <p>Useful groups include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Washing products.</li>
    <li>Stain treatment.</li>
    <li>Drying accessories.</li>
    <li>Cleaning supplies.</li>
    <li>Pet laundry items.</li>
    <li>Delicates and garment care.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Small baskets or tubs can keep these groups together. This makes it easier to pull out
    what you need without knocking over bottles or searching through the back of a cupboard.
  </p>
  <p>
    Storage tubs, labelled baskets, shelf organisers and laundry caddies can help here, but
    only after the cupboard has been sorted and measured.
  </p>

  <h2>Make drying space easier to manage</h2>
  <p>
    Drying clothes can be one of the biggest challenges in small Australian homes, especially
    during wet weather or in apartments without much outdoor space.
  </p>
  <p>Useful options may include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Foldable drying racks.</li>
    <li>Wall-mounted drying rails.</li>
    <li>Over-door drying racks.</li>
    <li>Peg airers for socks and small items.</li>
    <li>Indoor clothes horses.</li>
    <li>Retractable clotheslines.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    The best drying option depends on the home. A family laundry may need a large foldable
    drying rack, while a single-person apartment may only need a compact rail or over-door
    option.
  </p>
  <p>
    The key is to choose drying products that can be packed away when not in use. Permanent
    drying clutter can make a small laundry feel even smaller.
  </p>

  <h2>Use baskets for sorting, not storing indefinitely</h2>
  <p>
    Laundry baskets are useful, but too many baskets can take over the room. In a small
    laundry, baskets should support the washing routine rather than become long-term storage.
  </p>
  <p>A simple system might include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>One basket for dirty laundry.</li>
    <li>One basket for clean laundry.</li>
    <li>One small basket for delicates or hand-wash items.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Large families may need more sorting, but the same rule applies: every basket should have
    a clear purpose.
  </p>
  <p>
    If clean washing regularly sits in baskets for days, the issue may not be storage. It may
    be that the folding or putting-away routine needs to be made easier.
  </p>

  <h2>Keep the bench clear if you have one</h2>
  <p>
    A laundry bench is useful for folding, sorting and stain treatment. But if it becomes
    covered in bottles, baskets and random household items, it stops being useful.
  </p>
  <p>
    A practical approach is to keep the bench mostly clear and store products above, below or
    beside it.
  </p>
  <p>Items that may deserve bench space include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>A small stain-treatment tray.</li>
    <li>A laundry basket while folding.</li>
    <li>A small container for loose items found in pockets.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Everything else should have a proper storage spot.
  </p>
  <p>
    This is especially useful in homes where the laundry also functions as a mudroom, pet area
    or cleaning zone.
  </p>

  <h2>Use hooks for awkward items</h2>
  <p>
    Hooks are simple, cheap and useful in laundries. They work well for items that do not sit
    neatly on shelves.
  </p>
  <p>Good uses include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Hanging mops.</li>
    <li>Hanging brooms.</li>
    <li>Holding dustpans.</li>
    <li>Hanging reusable shopping bags.</li>
    <li>Holding pet leads or towels.</li>
    <li>Hanging ironing accessories.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Wall hooks, over-door hooks and adhesive hooks can all be useful, depending on the surface
    and weight of the item.
  </p>
  <p>
    Renters should be careful with adhesive products. They may remove cleanly from some
    surfaces but damage paint or laminate on others.
  </p>

  <h2>Store cleaning products safely</h2>
  <p>
    Laundry rooms often hold cleaning chemicals, so storage needs to be practical and safe.
  </p>
  <p>Cleaning products should generally be kept:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Upright.</li>
    <li>Away from heat.</li>
    <li>Away from direct sunlight.</li>
    <li>Out of reach of young children and pets.</li>
    <li>Away from food or pet food.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    If the laundry has low cupboards, child-safe locks may be worth considering in households
    with children.
  </p>
  <p>
    For small homes, it may be tempting to keep cleaning supplies wherever they fit. A better
    approach is to keep them grouped in a basket or caddy so they are easy to move and less
    likely to leak across shelves.
  </p>

  <h2>Create a spot for lost laundry items</h2>
  <p>
    Every laundry seems to collect loose coins, tissues, hair ties, buttons, receipts and
    small items from pockets.
  </p>
  <p>
    A small container or tray can help stop these items spreading across the bench. It does
    not need to be complicated. The goal is simply to give loose items one place to go.
  </p>
  <p>
    This is also useful for socks waiting for their missing pair.
  </p>

  <h2>Think about pet laundry separately</h2>
  <p>
    Homes with pets often need a laundry setup for towels, washable mats, bedding or cleaning
    cloths.
  </p>
  <p>
    It can help to keep pet laundry items separate from regular household laundry. This might
    include:
  </p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>A dedicated pet towel basket.</li>
    <li>A small tub for pet cleaning supplies.</li>
    <li>A washable mat near the laundry door.</li>
    <li>A drying spot for wet towels or leads.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    This helps prevent pet items from taking over the main laundry routine.
  </p>

  <h2>What to check before buying laundry storage products</h2>
  <p>Before buying laundry organisers, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>The actual measurements of the space.</li>
    <li>Whether the item needs drilling.</li>
    <li>Whether it can handle moisture.</li>
    <li>Whether it is easy to clean.</li>
    <li>Whether it solves a daily problem.</li>
    <li>Whether it can be moved if your setup changes.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Laundry storage should make the room easier to use, not just make it look tidy for a few
    days.
  </p>

  <h2>Final thoughts</h2>
  <p>
    The best laundry organisation ideas are usually the ones that remove a repeated
    annoyance. Use vertical space where it genuinely helps, group products by task, keep the
    bench usable and avoid filling a small room with products that only look tidy when empty.
  </p>
  <p>
    A small laundry can still work well if every item has a clear purpose and the most-used
    products are easy to reach. Start with the bottleneck, then improve one shelf, basket or
    corner at a time.
  </p>

